 (A) at (0,0);
 (B) at (4,0);
 (C) at (1.2,2);
 (D) at (1.2,0); % foot of altitude

 % Extended base (dashed)
 (A) – (-0.5,0);

 % Draw triangle
 (A) – (B) – (C) – cycle;

 % Draw altitude
 (C) – (D);

 % Right angle marker
 (1.2,0.2) – (1.4,0.2) – (1.4,0);

 % Labels
 at (A) {$A$};
 at (B) {$B$};
 at (C) {$C$};

 % Side labels
 at ($(A)!0.5!(C)$) {$b$};
 at ($(B)!0.5!(C)$) {$a$};
 at ($(A)!0.5!(B)$) {$c$};

 % Altitude label
 at ($(C)!0.5!(D)$) {$h$};

 % Angle B (obtuse)
 (3.5,0) arc (180:117:0.5);
 at (3.15,0.35) { $B$};
tikzpicture
Obtuse triangle case: The derivation still applies because $\sin(180° - B) = \sin B$.
figure

When angle $B$ is obtuse, the altitude from $C$ still lands on line $AB$, 
and the same algebra works. For the obtuse angle, we use the identity 
$\sin(180° - B) = \sin B$, which holds for all angles. The Law of Sines 
is valid for *all* triangles—acute, right, or obtuse.

