Given: angle $A$, side $a$ (opposite $A$), and side $b$ (adjacent to $A$).

**Step 1: Compute the critical height** $h = b\sin A$.

**Step 2: Follow this decision tree:**

center
tikzpicture[
 node distance=0.6cm and 0.8cm,
 decision/.style={diamond, draw, fill=AtlasTeal!15, text width=1.8cm, align=center, inner sep=1pt, font=},
 result/.style={rectangle, draw, rounded corners, fill=AtlasCoral!20, text width=2cm, align=center, minimum height=0.6cm, font=},
 stepbox/.style={rectangle, draw, fill=gray!10, text width=2cm, align=center, minimum height=0.5cm, font=},
 arrow/.style={->, thick, >=stealth}
]
 % Top decision: Is A acute or obtuse?
 (start) {Is $A$ acute?};

 % Acute branch (left side)
 (comp1) {Compare $a$ to $h$};

 % Results for acute case
 (r1) {$a < h$\\**No triangle**};
 (r2) {$a = h$\\**One triangle**\\(right $\triangle$)};
 (comp2) {Is $a < b$?};

 (r3) {Yes\\**Two triangles**};
 (r4) {No\\**One triangle**};

 % Obtuse branch (right side)
 (comp3) {Is $a > b$?};

 (r5) {No\\**No triangle**};
 (r6) {Yes\\**One triangle**};

 % Arrows
 (start) – node[above left, font=] {Yes} (comp1);
 (start) – node[above right, font=] {No (obtuse)} (comp3);

 (comp1) – node[left, font=] {$a < h$} (r1);
 (comp1) – node[right, font=] {$a = h$} (r2);
 (comp1) – node[right, font=] {$a > h$} (comp2);

 (comp2) – (r3);
 (comp2) – (r4);

 (comp3) – (r5);
 (comp3) – (r6);
tikzpicture
center

**Quick Summary:**

- **No triangle:** Side $a$ is too short to reach the opposite side

- **One triangle:** Either $a$ creates a right angle, or $a \geq b$ (acute $A$), or $a > b$ (obtuse $A$)

- **Two triangles:** Only when $A$ is acute and $h < a < b$

